ABACBS EMCR Hackathon - 1. Obtain annotated scRNA-seq pancreas reference

Shila Ghazanfar

01 November, 2024

Load packages and data

Load scripts and packages.

library(SingleCellExperiment) # for data structure
library(zellkonverter) # for reading scRNAseq h5ad data
library(scran) # for normalisation
library(scater) # for visualisation
library(randomForest) # for predictive model

In this document we take an annotated scRNA-seq pancreas dataset from the Tabula Sapiens compendium, downloaded from the cellxgene website. The direct download link can be found here. The data object is placed in the relative location ../rawData/.

We read the scRNA-seq data using the readH5AD() function to obtain a SingleCellExperiment object, assign rownames as gene symbols, normalise the counts according to overall library size, and then subset to features that are present in the pancreas MoleculeExperiment object.

me_feats = readRDS("../processedData/xenium_pancreas_features.Rds")
sce = readH5AD("../rawData/9af4585d-a1aa-4109-913f-6fe73772af70.h5ad",
               X_name = "counts")
sce

Examine the cell type annotation within this dataset with the reduced number of features.

pancreas_colours = setNames(c("#A83279", "#4C9F70", "#E5D352", "#BB77C1", "#42A1F7", 
                              "#F98B60", "#7D59CE", "#FFD23F", "#6D7F99", "#63B7AF",
                              "#EF6F6C", "#46B5B3", "#C1B2AB", "#D6E3C4", "#FF677D"),
                            sort(unique(sce$cell_type)))

sort(table(sce$cell_type))

##                     2100                     2431                     5534
sce <- runPCA(sce, ncomponents = 15)
sce <- runUMAP(sce)

g = plotReducedDim(sce, "UMAP", colour_by = "cell_type") + 
  scale_colour_manual(values = pancreas_colours)
g

Fit cell type prediction model

We will fit a relatively simple Random Forest model to predict cell type using the logcounts of the scRNA-seq data. We will use only the features that are common between the scRNA-seq and Xenium data.

fit = randomForest(x = t(as.matrix(assay(sce, "logcounts"))),
                   y = sce$cell_type)

Save the objects

We save the SingleCellExperiment object in the ../ProcessedData/ folder. We also save the fitted Random Forest object and place it in the ../analysisOutput/ folder.

saveRDS(sce, file = "../processedData/sc_pancreas_sce.Rds")
saveRDS(fit, file = "../analysisOutput/sc_cell_type_RF_fit.Rds")
saveRDS(pancreas_colours, file = "../analysisOutput/pancreas_colours.Rds")
